<div id="review_118353553" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/118353553" />
    <a title="Marleen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1616365-marleen"><img alt="Marleen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576835511p2/1616365.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/118353553?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marleen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marleen" href="/user/show/1616365-marleen">Marleen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780553818017" href="/book/show/4912444-the-death-maze">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer118353553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16004265852036303958">I love everything Ariana Franklin / Diana Norman writes. Everything. She’s so talented and has a knack for bringing riveting historical fiction come alive. <br/>Simply put, Franklin’s books are for me the definition of a captivating read. I’m especially very fond of the characters I meet on the page; they are colorful, quirky, well-fleshed and very human. <br/>The Middle-ages are such a dark time, no doubt about it. Here, notwithstanding that the author gives us glimpses of historical reality and we get a</span>
  <span id="freeText16004265852036303958" style="display:none">I love everything Ariana Franklin / Diana Norman writes. Everything. She’s so talented and has a knack for bringing riveting historical fiction come alive. <br />Simply put, Franklin’s books are for me the definition of a captivating read. I’m especially very fond of the characters I meet on the page; they are colorful, quirky, well-fleshed and very human. <br />The Middle-ages are such a dark time, no doubt about it. Here, notwithstanding that the author gives us glimpses of historical reality and we get a good idea of how horrific those times were, for women especially, she doesn’t write a dark book. No, on the contrary, this is a fictional historical crime novel that foremost brings a sense of adventure, but also entertainment – and the occasional insight into the human kind. The author is a genius when it comes to bringing strong women to the page and making them the center of a story. Adelia is a satisfyingly complex and independent character. She’s wonderful, flaws and all. I like it that there are real historical events and personalities in the “Mistress of the Art of Death” books; it’s like an incentive to learn more about 12th Century Europe. Most of all, I look forward reading more Adelia adventures.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16004265852036303958" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


