    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_54241040" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/54241040" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1951663-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1333653552p2/1951663.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/54241040?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/1951663-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9780143142874" href="/book/show/2436462.The_Serpent_s_Tale">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1951663-laura?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1951663-laura?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1951663-laura?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer54241040" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15854453954301363807">In <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/86643.Mistress_of_the_Art_of_Death__Book_1_' title='Mistress of the Art of Death (Book 1) by Ariana Franklin' rel='nofollow noopener'>Mistress of the Art of Death</a>, author <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/49612.Ariana_Franklin' title='Ariana Franklin' rel='nofollow noopener'>Ariana Franklin</a> introduced Adelia Aguilar, a 12th century physician with a speciality in what we now call forensic science. Franklin&apos;s obviously thorough research and excellent writing skills were put to good use in the creation of Adelia, her friends, her world, and the &quot;case&quot; she is called upon to resolve.<br/><br/>In <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1232140.The_Serpent_s_Tale__Mistress_of_the_Art_of_Death__Book_2_' title='The Serpent&apos;s Tale (Mistress of the Art of Death, Book 2) by Ariana Franklin' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Serpent&apos;s Tale</a>, those research and writing skills are still evident, but the people and places they are meant to describe are thin shadows of th</span>
  <span id="freeText15854453954301363807" style="display:none">In <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/86643.Mistress_of_the_Art_of_Death__Book_1_" title="Mistress of the Art of Death (Book 1) by Ariana Franklin" rel="nofollow noopener">Mistress of the Art of Death</a>, author <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/49612.Ariana_Franklin" title="Ariana Franklin" rel="nofollow noopener">Ariana Franklin</a> introduced Adelia Aguilar, a 12th century physician with a speciality in what we now call forensic science. Franklin's obviously thorough research and excellent writing skills were put to good use in the creation of Adelia, her friends, her world, and the "case" she is called upon to resolve.<br /><br />In <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1232140.The_Serpent_s_Tale__Mistress_of_the_Art_of_Death__Book_2_" title="The Serpent's Tale (Mistress of the Art of Death, Book 2) by Ariana Franklin" rel="nofollow noopener">The Serpent's Tale</a>, those research and writing skills are still evident, but the people and places they are meant to describe are thin shadows of those in the first book. Adelia herself has lost much of the strength and independence that made her such a memorable character, and her development is reduced to constantly repeated fear for her daughter and resentment of her daughter's father, Bishop Rowley Picot. The other characters lack even that much depth and are mainly props for a mystery that has potential but is stretched too thinly to hold the reader's interest throughout the book.<br /><br />Although I have heard good things about the third book, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3751995.Grave_Goods__Mistress_of_the_Art_of_Death__Book_3_" title="Grave Goods (Mistress of the Art of Death, Book 3) by Ariana Franklin" rel="nofollow noopener">Grave Goods</a>, it is purely the respect and interest carried over from Franklin's first book that makes me want to read it. Hopefully her abilities will shine again in the third book and this one can be set aside and forgotten. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15854453954301363807" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

