<div id="review_238988240" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/238988240" />
    <a title="Jamie Collins" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/321673-jamie-collins"><img alt="Jamie Collins" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1450191045p2/321673.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/238988240?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jamie Collins" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jamie Collins" href="/user/show/321673-jamie-collins">Jamie Collins</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/321673-jamie-collins?shelf=medieval">medieval</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/321673-jamie-collins?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/321673-jamie-collins?shelf=historical-mystery">historical-mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/321673-jamie-collins?shelf=plantagenet">plantagenet</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer238988240" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1116356537165319635">I enjoyed much of this book. The writing is quite good, particularly the dialogue. As with the first book, the author does a great job with the historical setting, depicting life during a harsh medieval English winter. I continue to enjoy the main characters. (The recap of the first book seemed unnecessarily detailed, but perhaps that&apos;s just because I read it not long ago.)<br/><br/>Unfortunately, the mystery centers around the legend that Eleanor of Aquitaine poisoned her husband&apos;s famous mistress, Rosam</span>
  <span id="freeText1116356537165319635" style="display:none">I enjoyed much of this book. The writing is quite good, particularly the dialogue. As with the first book, the author does a great job with the historical setting, depicting life during a harsh medieval English winter. I continue to enjoy the main characters. (The recap of the first book seemed unnecessarily detailed, but perhaps that's just because I read it not long ago.)<br /><br />Unfortunately, the mystery centers around the legend that Eleanor of Aquitaine poisoned her husband's famous mistress, Rosamund Clifford.<br /><br />The portrayal of Henry II in his cameo appearance was nicely done. It's obvious that the author admires Henry and his accomplishments, and this admiration seems to mean that anyone who opposed the king must have been wicked or a fool. The depiction of Eleanor is terrible, and it nearly ruined the book for me. This amazing woman is reduced to a stupid, self-absorbed, flighty, jealous shrew whose closest adviser wheedles and lectures her like she's a toddler.<br /><br />The author does generously give Eleanor credit for promoting the value of women by encouraging courtly songs and poems. But otherwise, shame on Eleanor for betraying poor Henry, when all he wanted was to bring justice to his people and to take a nice, fat woman to bed. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Yes, Rosamund the Fair is obese. Eleanor holds a vigil, waiting for Rosamund's body to decompose, which she seems to think will happen within a couple of hours. It's gross and bizarre. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="1116356537165319635" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


